# Nineteen 5.0 - testnet ready!

@deleted-role 

Today we release Nineteen 5.0 Beta for testnet! 

A huge amount of work has been poured into the development, with lots of amazing things for all of bittensor to benefit from. A few highlights:

- The first bittensor-less subnet is here! No Bittensor package required - instead we use Fiber, purpose built for subnets. All subnets will be able to use this package, it's built for all
- With Fiber, Communication is encrypted, we're not tied to python, miners can handle DDOS much easier, we save 100's of miliseconds on each query, we can scale much better, and handle loads more queries
- Full rewrite of all code for modular, scalable architecture. Validator's organic API's can be scaled independently to handle as much organic traffic as possible 
- Fully dockerised deployment for validators, with an easy setup script. It's as simple as `docker compose up`!
- We can plug in new tasks so much more easily, with simple config changes

+ much, much more

Testnet code: https://github.com/namoray/nineteen
Fiber: https://github.com/namoray/fiber.git
Fiber docs:  https://fiber.sn19.ai/
SN19 Deck: https://sn19.ai/pdfs/sn19-deck.pdf

We'll be adding even more features over the next week or so, and make continual improvements based on any beta usage feedback. Minimum of 10 days in testnet for all to play with.

I wanted to highlight a couple of cool features that come off the back of nineteen 5.0

## Cursor support
You can now very easily use Cursor to plug into subnet 19's text models - using the super optimised miner output to directly help you build / mine / validate / make subnets

Here's a guide on using the testnet validator to wet your apetite - though of course it will much be faster when we plug into real miners

@namoray i have investigated fiber
I would like to understand a few choices you made there

To setup a connection from a validator to a miner, the validator first executes a handshake algorithm with the node to negotiate a symmetric key. It does not look like a standardized diffie-hellman exchange, but rather a protocol in which the validator generates the secret and uses the publickey of the miner to encrypt this shared key after which it sends it to the miner. After the handshake indeed both parties have possession of a secret key in which no man in the middle attack can occur, under the assumption that the implementation is correct.

Then all endpoints have a specialized header where a symmetric key UUID and the S58 adress of the validator is stored, the miner can use simple decryption to verify that it actually receiving requests from the right validator

# Nineteen 5.0 is here!

Incredibly excited, the long awaited first subnet to no longer use the bittensor package is here - history is made!

# Validators 

The proxy server needs migrating to our new repo. Here is the script :
https://github.com/namoray/nineteen/blob/production/migrate.sh

With autoupdate (Highly highly recommended, especially with child hotkeys, please reach out if you want support)
```bash
cd ~
deactivate
git clone https://github.com/namoray/nineteen.git
cd nineteen
sudo -E ./bootstrap.sh
source $HOME/.bashrc
pm2 delete all
cat ~/vision/.default.env  # Or however you want to view your old config
python core/create_config.py
```

Without  - :[
```bash
cd ~
deactivate
git clone https://github.com/namoray/nineteen.git
cd nineteen
WITH_AUTOUPDATES=0 sudo -E ./bootstrap.sh
source $HOME/.bashrc
pm2 delete all
cat ~/vision/.default.env  # Or however you want to view your old config
python core/create_config.py
```

## Orchestrator
autoupdates should handle it - but please confirm it's working

```bash
sudo -E bash bootstrap.sh
```

On the GPU server should get it up and running!
If you don't want autoupdates then please just 
```bash
git pull
./launch_orchestrator.sh
```
